# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: javalin-java
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] See the migration guide for details on upgrading from Javalin 6.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Javalin follows semantic versioning, meaning there are no breaking changes unless the major (leftmost) digit changes, for example `6.X.X` to `7.X.X`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Check out the AI instructions for Claude Code, Cursor, Copilot, and more.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] If you want Javalin with testing tools, Jackson and Logback, you can use the artifact id `javalin-bundle` instead of `javalin`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Javalin core is a single `javalin` artifact, with optional satellite modules you add only when you need them.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] For example, `javalin-bundle` packages the core with Jackson, Logback, and test tools; the per-engine `javalin-rendering-*` artifacts add template rendering; `javalin-micrometer` adds metrics; and `javalin-ssl` provides simplified SSL/TLS setup.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Every satellite module tracks the same version as `javalin` itself, and you can use the `javalin-bom` module to pin one version and have every `io.javalin:*` dependency resolve to it automatically.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] See the full module list at /download#javalin-modules.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Javalin has three main handler types: before-handlers, endpoint-handlers, and after-handlers.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] (There are also exception-handlers and error-handlers, but we’ll get to them later).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `Handler` interface has a void return type.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You use a method like `ctx.result(result)`, `ctx.json(obj)`, or `ctx.future(future)` to set the response which will be returned to the user.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] If you add multiple before/after handlers for the same path, they will be executed in the order they were added.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] This can be useful for adding authentication, caching, logging, etc.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can learn about how Javalin handles concurrency in FAQ - Concurrency.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Before-handlers are matched before every request (including static files).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] In some cases, you might want to only run a before-handler if the request will be matched (not 404).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Endpoint handlers are the main handler type, and defines your API.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can add a GET handler to serve data to a client, or a POST handler to receive some data.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Common methods are supported via `config.routes` (GET, POST, QUERY, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, HEAD, OPTIONS), uncommon operations (TRACE, CONNECT) are supported via `config.routes.addHttpHandler`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The QUERY method is similar to GET, but allows a request body.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] This is useful for complex queries that don’t fit in a URL.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Endpoint-handlers are matched in the order they are defined.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Handler paths can include path-parameters.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] However, you cannot extract the value of a wildcard.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Use a slash accepting path-parameter (`<param-name>` instead of `{param-name}`) if you need this behavior.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] In Javalin 7, `HandlerType` is a record instead of an enum, which means you can create custom HTTP methods dynamically using `HandlerType.findOrCreate("METHOD_NAME")`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] This is useful for protocols like WebDAV that use non-standard HTTP methods such as `PROPFIND`, `MKCOL`, `LOCK`, etc.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Custom methods work with all Javalin features including path parameters, roles, before/after handlers, and exception handling.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Method names must consist of uppercase letters only (e.g.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] In some cases, you might want to only run an after-handler if the request will be matched (not 404).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Wrapper-handlers run “around” endpoint handlers.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `HandlerWrapper` functional interface receives an `Endpoint` (with `method`, `path`, and `handler`) and returns a new `Handler` that wraps the original.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `Context` object provides you with everything you need to handle a http-request.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] It contains the underlying servlet-request and servlet-response, and a bunch of getters and setters.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] App data can be registered on the Javalin instance through `Javalin#create`, then accessed through the `appData(...)` method in `Context`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You need to create a typed key for your data, and then register it on the Javalin instance.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] It can be helpful to store the key as a static field, but you can also recreate the key every time you need it.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] At the end of the request-cycle, the cookie-store-map is serialized, base64-encoded and written to the response as a cookie.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Since the client stores the cookie, the `get` request to `serverTwoApp` will be able to retrieve the information that was passed in the `post` to `serverOneApp`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Please note that cookies have a max-size of 4kb.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Javalin has a very intuitive way of handling WebSockets.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The different flavors of `WsContext` expose different things, for example, `WsMessageContext` has the method `.message()` which gives you the message that the client sent.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The differences between the different contexts is small, and a full overview can be seen in the WsContext section.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can learn about how Javalin handles WebSocket concurrency in FAQ - Concurrency.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `config.routes.wsBefore` adds a handler that runs before a WebSocket handler.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can have as many before-handlers as you want per WebSocket endpoint, and all events are supported.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] A WebSocket endpoint is declared with `config.routes.ws(path, handler)`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] WebSocket handlers require unique paths.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `config.routes.wsAfter` adds a handler that runs after a WebSocket handler.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can have as many after-handlers as you want per WebSocket endpoint, and all events are supported.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `config.routes.wsBeforeUpgrade` adds a handler that runs before the WebSocket upgrade is attempted.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] This is an HTTP handler (not a WsConfig handler), so you have access to the regular `Context`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] It’s useful for authentication, validation, or rejecting upgrade requests before they happen.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `config.routes.wsAfterUpgrade` adds a handler that runs after the WebSocket upgrade is attempted.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Like `wsBeforeUpgrade`, this is an HTTP handler with access to the regular `Context`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `WsContext` object provides you with everything you need to handle a websocket-request.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] It contains the underlying websocket session and servlet-request, and convenience methods for sending messages to the client.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can group your endpoints by using the `apiBuilder()` and `path()` methods.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] The `apiBuilder()` methods creates a temporary static instance of Javalin, so that you can skip the `app.` or `router.` prefix before your handlers.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] This is equivalent to calling `ApiBuilder.get(app/router, ...)`, which translates to `app/router.get(...)`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] It is **not** a global singleton that holds static information, so you can use this safely in multiple locations and from multiple threads.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can import all the HTTP methods with `import static io.javalin.apibuilder.ApiBuilder.*`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Note that `path()` prefixes your paths with `/` (if you don’t add it yourself).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can attach `RouteRole`s to every endpoint inside a `path()` block by passing a `Collection<RouteRole>` as the second argument.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Roles applied at an outer `path(...)` are inherited by nested `path(...)` blocks, and any roles supplied at a nested level are merged (and deduplicated) with the inherited ones.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] This applies to HTTP handlers as well as `ws(...)` and `sse(...)`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can also create your own validator manually through `Validator.create(clazz, value, fieldName)`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Javalin used to have a functional interface `AccessManager`, which let you set per-endpoint authentication and/or authorization.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] In Javalin 6, this has been replaced with the `beforeMatched` handler.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can read more about this in the Javalin 5 to 6 migration guide.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] If you’re using `apiBuilder`, you can also scope roles to a `path()` block to apply them to every endpoint inside.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Javalin comes with a built in class called `HttpResponseException`, which can be used for default responses.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] If the client accepts JSON, a JSON object is returned.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Otherwise a plain text response is returned.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] You can include a `Map<String, String>` of details if you wish.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 302 Found response with the default title `Redirected`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 400 Bad Request response with the default title `Bad request`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 401 Unauthorized response with the default title `Unauthorized`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 403 Forbidden response with the default title `Forbidden`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 404 Not Found response with the default title `Not found`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 405 Method Not Allowed response with the default title `Method not allowed`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 409 Conflict response with the default title `Conflict`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 410 Gone response with the default title `Gone`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 429 Too Many Requests response with the default title `Too many requests`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 500 Internal Server Error response with the default title `Internal server error`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 502 Bad Gateway response with the default title `Bad gateway`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 503 Service Unavailable response with the default title `Service unavailable`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] Returns a 504 Gateway Timeout response with the default title `Gateway timeout`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] All handlers (before, endpoint, after, ws) can throw `Exception` (and any subclass of `Exception`).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p01] This can be useful if you, for example, want one set of error handlers for HTML, and one for JSON.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Server-sent events (often also called event source) are very simple in Javalin.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] `sendData` emits an SSE message without an `event:` field, so browsers fire the generic `message` event for it (rather than a named event like with `sendEvent`).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Data is serialized the same way as `sendEvent` — an `InputStream` is passed through as-is, anything else is serialized via the configured JSON mapper.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can pass a config object when creating a new instance of Javalin.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] All available subconfigs are explained in the sections below.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin uses standard servlet file upload handling to deal with multipart requests.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] This allows for configuring the maximum size for each individual file, the maximum size for the entire request, the maximum size of file to handle via in-memory upload and the cache directory to write uploaded files to if they exceed this limit.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can add a HTTP request logger by calling `config.requestLogger.http()`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can add a WebSocket logger by calling `config.requestLogger.ws()`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] The method takes a the same arguments as a normal `config.routes.ws()` call, and can be used to log events of all types.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] The logger runs after the WebSocket handler for the endpoint.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Single page application (SPA) mode is similar to static file handling.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] It runs after endpoint matching, and after static file handling.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] It’s basically a very fancy 404 mapper, which converts any 404’s into a specified page.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can define multiple single page handlers for your application by specifying different root paths.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can enabled single page mode by doing `config.spaRoot.addFile("/root", "/path/to/file.html")`, and/or `config.spaRoot.addFile("/root", "/path/to/file.html", Location.EXTERNAL)`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can enable static file serving by doing `config.staticFiles.add("/directory", location)`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Static resource handling is done **after** endpoint matching, meaning your own GET endpoints have higher priority.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can call `config.staticFiles.add(...)` multiple times to set up multiple handlers.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] No configuration is shared between handlers.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] WebJars can be enabled by calling `config.staticFiles.enableWebjars()`, they will be available at `/webjars/name/version/file.ext`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] WebJars can be found on https://www.webjars.org/.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Everything available through NPM is also available through WebJars.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] This is useful if you want to use Javalin with a different embedded server, or if you want to avoid Jetty-specific dependencies for static file handling.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin does not have a logger included, which means that you have to add your own logger.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] The `app.start()` method spawns a user thread, starts the server, and then returns.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Your program will not exit until this thread is terminated by calling `app.stop()`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin’s default Jetty server includes a `StatisticsHandler`, so graceful shutdown works out of the box.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] When `app.stop()` is called, the server will wait for active requests to complete before shutting down.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Read about how to configure sessions in our session tutorial.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can configure your embedded jetty-server with a handler-chain (example), and Javalin will attach it’s own handlers to the end of this chain.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin now has a SSL plugin: https://javalin.io/plugins/ssl-helpers.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] It’s recommended to use this plugin for setting up SSL and HTTP2/3, as it’s a lot more user-friendly than configuring it manually in Jetty.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] To configure SSL or HTTP2 manually in Jetty you need to use a custom server.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] An example of a custom server with SSL can be found in the examples, HelloWorldSecure.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin has events for server start/stop, as well as for when handlers are added.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin has a plugin system, which lets you add functionality to Javalin.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You do this by extending the `Plugin` class and overriding the methods you’re interested in.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] See the plugins page for more information about plugins.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] The Javalin request lifecycle is pretty straightforward.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] There is a very simple rate limiter included in Javalin, available via `RateLimitPlugin`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Different endpoints can have different rate limits.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Due to Jetty 11+ not working on Android, Javalin 5+ (which uses Jetty 11 or 12) is not compatible, but Javalin 4 is.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can find the docs for Javalin 4 here.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can check the status of Jetty 11+ on Android here.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] If your JRE supports project Loom, Javalin will use a `newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor` for serving requests if you set the `config.concurrency.useVirtualThreads = true` config option.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Otherwise, a `QueuedThreadPool` with 250 threads will be used.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Each incoming request is handled by a dedicated thread, so all Handler implementations should be thread-safe.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] This default configuration allows Javalin to handle up to 250 concurrent requests, which is generally more than enough (keep in mind, most requests are much shorter than 1 second).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] If your application involves numerous long-running requests, consider exploring Asynchronous requests or investigate setting up Javalin with project Loom, detailed in the Loomylin repository.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] In cases where you use `ctx.future()` or `ctx.async()`, the thread will be returned to the thread pool while the asynchronous task is running.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Consequently, the request might be handled by a different thread when the asynchronous task is completed.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] If you are uncertain whether your application requires asynchronous requests, it’s likely not necessary.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] The default configuration provides similar performance to Jetty, which can handle over a million plaintext requests per second.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] WebSocket operates over TCP, so messages will arrive at the server in the order that they were sent by the client.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin then handles the messages from a given WebSocket connection sequentially.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Therefore, the order that messages are handled is guaranteed to be the same as the order the client sent them in.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] However, different connections will be handled in parallel on multiple threads, so the WebSocket event handlers should be thread-safe.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] People often ask how to test Javalin apps.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Since Javalin is just a library, you can instantiate and start the server programmatically.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] There is a tutorial at /tutorials/testing which goes through some different types of tests (unit tests, functional/integration tests, ui/end-to-end tests).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can read it to get some ideas for how to test your app.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] There is a Javadoc available at javadoc.io.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Please contribute to the Javadoc if you can.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] To deploy Javalin, simply create a jar with dependencies, then launch the jar with `java -jar filename.jar`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin has an embedded server, so you don’t need an application server.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin is primarily meant to be used with the embedded Jetty server, but if you want to run Javalin on another web server (such as Tomcat), you can use Maven or Gradle to exclude Jetty, and attach Javalin as a servlet.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] While the default ThreadPool (250 threads) is enough for most use cases, sometimes slow operations should be run asynchronously.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Luckily it’s very easy in Javalin, just pass a `Supplier<CompletableFuture>` to `ctx.future()`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin will automatically switch between sync and async modes to handle the different tasks.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Imagine that we have a random cat fact API that we want to call on behalf of a client.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] We’ll start by creating a simple method to call the API, which returns a `CompletableFuture<String>` which will resolve either to a cat fact or an error.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] By calling `ctx.future(supplier)` you are not putting Javalin in an async state.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] It’s a simple setter method, which makes it possible for Javalin to call the given supplier and switch into async mode at an appropriate time.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] The `ctx.future()` method works great if you are using a `CompletableFuture` based API, like Java’s `HttpClient`, but if you have long running tasks which aren’t `CompletableFuture` based, you might want to try the `ctx.async(runnable)` (see next section).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] If you want to execute a blocking task outside of the server ThreadPool, you can use `ctx.async()`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin will immediately start an async context and run the task on a dedicated executor service.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] It will resume the normal request flow (after-handlers, request-logging) once the task is done.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] To configure the JsonMapper, you need to pass an object which implements the `JsonMapper` interface to `config.jsonMapper()`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin uses Jackson as the default JSON mapper.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin is designed to work with other `Servlet` and `Filter` instances running on the Jetty Server.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Filters are pretty straightforward to add, since they don’t finish the request.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] After opening `http://localhost:7000/proxy/` you will see Javalin site (but with broken styles because of file paths).
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Each Javalin instance has a `FileRenderer` attached to it.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] This method is called when you call `Context#render`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] The default `FileRenderer` of Javalin is a singleton named `JavalinRenderer`, see the section below for more information.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin offers separate per-engine artifacts for template rendering (e.g.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] `javalin-rendering-freemarker`, `javalin-rendering-velocity`, `javalin-rendering-thymeleaf`, etc.), which follow the same version as the `javalin` artifact.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You can learn more about this at /plugins/rendering.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] If you don’t want to deal with NPM and frontend builds, Javalin has support for simplified Vue.js development.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] When you put `.vue` files in `src/main/resources/vue`, Javalin will scan the folder and register the components in your `<head>` tag.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] This will give you a lot of the benefits of a modern frontend architecture, with very few of the downsides.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] There are more extensive docs at /plugins/javalinvue, and there is an in-depth tutorial at /tutorials/simple-frontends-with-javalin-and-vue.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] If you encounter `TimeoutExceptions` and `ClosedChannelExceptions` in your DEBUG logs, this is nothing to worry about.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Typically, a browser will keep the HTTP connection open until the server terminates it.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] When this happens is decided by the server’s `idleTimeout` setting, which is 30 seconds by default in Jetty/Javalin.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Javalin has a default error handler for `java.lang.Error` that will log the error and return a 500.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] A lot of people use Javalin for Minecraft servers, and they often have issues with Jetty and WebSockets.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Please consider consulting our Minecraft tutorial if you’re working with Javalin and a Minecraft server.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Using relocate is not required, but it can easily conflict with other plugin dependencies.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] If this is a publicly released plugin, this step is recommended to make Javalin work on a different Minecraft Server.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] RemoteAPI can usually use the class loader of the main class of the plugin.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] On Bukkit and Spigot it is a class extends `org.bukkit.plugin.java#JavaPlugin`, on BungeeCord and WaterFall it is a class extends `net.md_5.bungee.api.plugin#Plugin`.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Get it via `{your plugin's main class}.class.getClassLoader()` .
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] After switching the class loader, you may still receive a missing dependency error from Javalin.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You only need to add the corresponding dependency as prompted in the Javalin log.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Docs for 6.7.0 (last 6.X version) can be found here.
[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] Docs for 5.6.X (last 5.X version) can be found here.
