[src:javalin-java/documentation-p02] You've reached the end of the docs, congratulations.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:javalin-java/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] Jetty started as an independent open-source project in 1995.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] Jetty often provides support for web services in an embedded Java application and it is already a component of the Eclipse IDE.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] It provides support for a wide variety of specifications and protocols including JASPI, JMX, JNDI, OSGi, WebSocket, HTTP/2, and more.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] Originally developed by software engineer Greg Wilkins, Jetty was an HTTP server component of Mort Bay Server.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] It was originally called IssueTracker (its original application) and then MBServler (Mort Bay Servlet server).
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] Neither of these were much liked, so Jetty was finally picked.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] Jetty was started in 1995 and was hosted by MortBay, creating version 1.x and 2.x, until 2000.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] From 2000 to 2005, Jetty was hosted by sourceforge.net where version 3.x, 4.x, and 5.x were produced.
[src:javalin-java/jetty-web-server] In 2005, the entire Jetty project moved to codehaus.org.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced Kotlin had become its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Since the release of Android Studio 3.0 in October 2017, Kotlin has been included as an alternative to the standard Java compiler.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin has support for the web with Kotlin/JS, through an intermediate representation-based backend that has been declared stable since version 1.8, released in December 2022.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin/Native (e.g., Apple silicon support) has been declared stable since version 1.9.20, released in November 2023.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] The name is derived from Kotlin Island, a Russian island in the Gulf of Finland, near Saint Petersburg.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Andrey Breslav, Kotlin's former lead designer, mentioned that the team decided to name it after an island, in imitation of the Java programming language, which shares a name with the Indonesian island of Java.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] The first commit to the Kotlin Git repository was on 8 November 2010.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] In July 2011, JetBrains unveiled Project Kotlin, a new JVM language that had been under development for a year.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains lead Dmitry Jemerov said that most languages lacked the features they were looking for, except for Scala.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] However, he cited Scala's slow compilation time as a deficiency.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] One of Kotlin's stated goals is to compile as quickly as Java.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] In February 2012, JetBrains open-sourced the project under the Apache 2 license.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains expected Kotlin to drive sales of IntelliJ IDEA.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.0 was released on 15 February 2016, which is considered the first officially stable release, and JetBrains has committed to long-term backwards compatibility starting with this version.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] At Google I/O 2017, Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced that Kotlin is now its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Development lead Andrey Breslav has said that Kotlin is designed to be an industrial-strength object-oriented language, a "better language" than Java, and still fully interoperable with Java code, allowing companies to make a gradual migration from Java to Kotlin.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Semicolons are optional as a statement terminator; in most cases, a newline is sufficient for the compiler to deduce that the statement has ended.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin variable declarations and parameter lists place the data type after the variable name (separated by a colon), similar to Ada, BASIC, Pascal, TypeScript, and Rust.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.3 added support for contracts, which are stable for the standard library declarations, but still experimental for user-defined declarations.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Contracts are inspired by the design-by-contract programming paradigm.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Like Scala.js, Kotlin code can be transpiled to JavaScript, enabling interoperability between Kotlin and JavaScript and allowing either writing complete web applications in Kotlin or sharing code between a Kotlin backend and a JavaScript frontend.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin relaxes the Java restriction on static methods and variables, allowing them to exist outside a class body.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Static objects and functions can be defined at the top level of the package without requiring a redundant class-level scope.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] For compatibility with Java, Kotlin provides the `JvmName` annotation, which specifies the class name used when the package is viewed from a Java project.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] For example, `@file:JvmName("JavaClassName")`.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] As in C, C++, C#, Java, and Go, the entry point to a Kotlin program is a function named `main`, which may be passed an array containing any command-line arguments.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Perl, PHP, and Unix shell–style string interpolation is supported.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin provides the following keywords to restrict visibility for top-level declarations (such as classes) and for class members: `public`, `internal`, `protected`, and `private`.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin distinguishes between nullable and non-nullable data types.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] All nullable objects must be declared with a "?" postfix after the type name.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin supports higher-order functions and anonymous functions, or **lambdas**.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] If a lambda takes parameters, they are declared within the braces and followed by the -> operator.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin Multiplatform enables a single codebase to target multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, the web, Android, and iOS.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Compose Multiplatform is a multiplatform UI framework based on Jetpack Compose.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] It is Jetpack Compose for Android ported to Windows, macOS, Linux, web, and iOS.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Jetpack Compose uses a Kotlin compiler plugin to transform composable functions into UI elements.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] For example, the Text composable function displays a text label on the screen.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] In 2018, Kotlin was the fastest-growing language on GitHub, with 2.6 times as many developers as in 2017.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] It is the fourth-most-loved programming language according to the 2020 Stack Overflow Developer Survey.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin was also awarded the O'Reilly Open Source Software Conference Breakout Award for 2019.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] A large number of companies in various industries use Kotlin, including Google, Amazon Web Services, Netflix and McDonald's.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] When Kotlin was announced as an official Android development language at Google I/O in May 2017, it became the third language fully supported for Android, after Java and C++.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] As of 2020, Kotlin was the most widely used language on Android, with Google estimating that 70% of the top 1,000 apps on the Play Store were written in Kotlin.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Google itself had 60 apps written in Kotlin, including Maps and Drive.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Many Android apps, such as Google Home, were in the process of migrating to Kotlin and therefore use both Kotlin and Java.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin on Android is seen as beneficial for its null-safety and features that make code shorter and more readable.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Ktor is a JetBrains Kotlin-first framework for building server and client applications.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] The Spring Framework officially added Kotlin support with version 5, on 4 January 2017.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] To further support Kotlin, Spring has translated all its documentation into Kotlin and added built-in support for many Kotlin-specific features, such as coroutines.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] In 2020, JetBrains found in a survey of developers who use Kotlin that 56% used it for mobile apps, while 47% used it for a web backend.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Just over a third of all Kotlin developers said they were migrating from another language.
[src:javalin-java/kotlin-programming-language] Most Kotlin users targeted Android (or the JVM), with only 6% using Kotlin Native.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:javalin-java/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:javalin-java/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
